PK, ab JWT ko bhi same framework me samjhte hain (Evolution of Pain + Feynman).
JWT tabhi feel aata hai jab Session vs JWT ka pain samajh aata hai.

JWT (JSON Web Token)
1️⃣ Evolution of Pain (JWT se pehle kya problem thi)

Earlier web apps Session ID authentication use karte the.

Flow

User login karta tha:

username
password

Server karta tha:

1️⃣ verify user
2️⃣ session create
3️⃣ DB me store

Example DB record:

session_id: abc123
user_id: 45
roles: admin
expiry: 2 hours

Client ko milta tha:

session_id = abc123

Aur har request me cookie me send hota tha.

Nightmare Scenario (Distributed Systems)

Ab imagine karo:

10 application servers

Aur:

3 database clusters

Har request me server ko:

DB query karni padegi

To validate session.

Problems:

1️⃣ DB bottleneck
2️⃣ Latency increase
3️⃣ Session replication problem
4️⃣ Horizontal scaling difficult

Yahi pain solve karne ke liye JWT aaya.

2️⃣ The Cure (JWT)

JWT idea simple hai:

Store session data inside token

Instead of DB lookup.

Server token verify karega, DB call nahi karega.

Isliye JWT:

Stateless authentication
3️⃣ JWT Flow (Real System)
Step 1 — Login

Client:

username
password

Authentication server verify karta hai.

Step 2 — Token Generate

Server generate karta hai:

JWT token

Example:

eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9
.
eyJzdWIiOiIxMjM0NTY3ODkwIiwiZXhwIjoxNzAwMDAwfQ
.
SflKxwRJSMeKKF2QT4fwpMeJf36POk6yJV_adQssw5c
Step 3 — Client stores token

Usually:

localStorage
cookie
Step 4 — API Request

Client sends request:

GET /user
Authorization: Bearer <JWT>
Step 5 — Server verifies token

Server:

1️⃣ verify signature
2️⃣ check expiry
3️⃣ read user info

Agar valid:

Access granted
4️⃣ JWT Structure

JWT 3 parts se bana hota hai.

HEADER.PAYLOAD.SIGNATURE

Example:

xxxxx.yyyyy.zzzzz
Part 1 — Header

Metadata.

Example:

{
 "alg": "HS256",
 "typ": "JWT"
}

Meaning:

Field	Meaning
alg	signing algorithm
typ	token type
Part 2 — Payload

User information store hoti hai.

Example:

{
 "sub": "12345",
 "email": "pk@gmail.com",
 "role": "admin",
 "exp": 1710000000
}

Payload me claims hote hain.

Types of Claims
1️⃣ Registered claims

Standard fields.

Examples:

iss → issuer
sub → subject (user id)
aud → audience
exp → expiry
iat → issued at
2️⃣ Public claims

Custom but widely understood.

Example:

email
role
country
3️⃣ Private claims

Internal data.

Example:

internal_permission
auth_server_flag

Sirf internal services use karte hain.

Part 3 — Signature

Signature ensure karti hai:

Token tampered nahi hua

Signature generate hoti hai:

hash(
 base64(header)
 +
 base64(payload)
 +
 secret_key
)

Example:

HMACSHA256(
 base64UrlEncode(header) + "." +
 base64UrlEncode(payload),
 secret
)
Important Thing

JWT encoded hota hai.

Base64 encoded

Encrypted nahi.

Isliye payload read ho sakta hai.

Example:

jwt.io

Pe paste karo → payload visible.

Isliye password kabhi JWT me store nahi karna.

5️⃣ JWT Advantages
Stateless

Server ko DB check nahi karna.

Fast

Validation:

signature check
expiry check
Scalable

Perfect for:

microservices
distributed systems
Self-contained

Token me already hota hai:

user id
roles
permissions
expiry
6️⃣ JWT Problems (Important Interview Topic)
Problem 1 — Token Revocation

User ban ho gaya.

But token valid hai:

exp = tomorrow

Server ko kaise pata chale?

Solution 1 — Blacklist

Store:

revoked_token_ids

Problem:

DB lookup again

JWT ka benefit khatam.

Solution 2 — Short lived tokens

Example:

Access token → 10 minutes
Refresh token → 7 days

Very common solution.

Problem 2 — Payload visible

JWT:

encoded
not encrypted

Solution:

JWE (JSON Web Encryption)
Problem 3 — Key rotation

Agar secret leak ho jaye.

Solution:

kid (key id)

Multiple public keys maintain karte hain.

7️⃣ JWT vs Session
Feature	Session	JWT
state	stateful	stateless
storage	DB	token
scaling	hard	easy
speed	slower	faster
revocation	easy	difficult
8️⃣ JWT in Real Systems

JWT use hota hai:

OAuth
Google login
Facebook login
Microservices

API gateway JWT verify karta hai.

Single Sign On (SSO)

Login once.

Access:

app1
app2
app3

Same token.

9️⃣ Real Architecture (HLD)

Typical flow:

Client
   │
   │ login
   ▼
Auth Server
   │
   │ JWT
   ▼
Client
   │
   │ request + JWT
   ▼
API Gateway
   │
   │ verify JWT
   ▼
Microservices
🔟 Mental Model

JWT ko yaad rakhne ka simple rule:

Session → server stores state
JWT → client carries state

PK agar chaho to main 3 cheeze aur deep explain kar sakta hoon jo JWT + security interviews me bahut puchi jaati hain:

1️⃣ Access Token vs Refresh Token (real production flow)
2️⃣ How Google / OAuth JWT authentication actually works internally
3️⃣ JWT security attacks (alg=none, key confusion, replay attack)

Ye system design + backend interviews me direct puchte hain.